flowRoot.flowPara: Welcome
• Welcome screen that opens when Piper is started.
• Lists all recognized devices.
• Selecting a device allows it to be configured in the next screen.
• When only one device is connected, the welcome screen is skipped.
Select a device to configure it
• Default stack page that is shown when a device has been selected.
• Shows the current mice, without button assignment as this is not required for the resolution.
• Profile button in top left opens a popover to select the current profile.
• The back button goes back to the welcome page.
• Clicking on a list row opens a dialog to set that resolution.
• The + row adds a new resolution if the device allows this. It is not shown if the device has a static number of resolutions.
• The x appears on hover and deletes the list row with its assigned resolution. It is not shown if the device has a static number of resolutions.
• Assigning a resolution will most likely go through a macro (not available on all devices -- how do we deal with that?).
• The popover shows all available profiles.
• Clicking a profile switches to that profile.
• The currently active profile is pre-selected.
• The Add Profile button is insensitive if the device only supports a static number of profiles.
• Clicking the x removes that profile, if supported by the device.
• A checkmark is shown on the default profile.
• A checkmark is shown on hover on other rows; clicking it makes that profile the default.
• Do we allow to disable profiles on devices that support it?
• Stack page to remap a mice's buttons.
• Shows the current mice, with button assignment as this is required to understand the mapping.
• All buttons are listed; if there are too many the list will scroll.
• Clicking on a list row opens a dialog to remap that row's button.

• Stack page to set a mice's LEDs.
• It would be fun to make the color in the SVG change depending on the selection.
•It would also be nice if there is an LED mapping in the SVG, similar to the button mapping.
• Clicking on an effect selects it and opens the configuration popover.
• The color button opens a regular GtkColorChooserDialog to pick colors.
• Welcome screen that opens when Piper is started and no devices are found.
